AIJAH Docker Strategy and Roadmap
Current State
The project is 100% specification -- 6 design docs, zero implementation. No docker-compose.yml, no Dockerfiles, no backend code, no frontend code, no SQL migrations, no sandbox folder. This is actually ideal: you can set up Docker correctly from the start rather than retrofitting it later.
The V1 contract already defines a 4-service Docker Compose stack:
frontend (:3000) -- static HTML/JS via nginx
backend (:8000) -- Python 3.11 + FastAPI
postgres (:5432) -- PostgreSQL 16
ollama (:11434) -- local LLM runtime

Part 1: What the Docker Person Can Do in Parallel (and When)
Immediately (before any backend code exists)
The Docker person does NOT need to wait for the coder to start. These tasks are standalone:
Write docker-compose.yml with all 4 services, volumes, networks, environment variables -- the contract in V1_CONTRACT.md lines 37-73 gives the exact outline
Write backend/Dockerfile -- even with just a "hello world" FastAPI stub, the Dockerfile structure is the same whether the app has 1 route or 50
Write frontend/Dockerfile-- nginx serving a staticindex.html placeholder
Write .dockerignore files for both backend/ and frontend/ (exclude __pycache, .git, node_modules, *.pyc, etc.)
Create the sandbox/ directory with test files inside it (fake invoices, folders) for end-to-end testing later
Create backend/db/migrations/001_create_enums.sql and 002_create_tables.sql using the exact schemas from V1_CONTRACT.md and TYPE_LEDGER.md
Create backend/db/seed.sql -- insert a test user and device row
Get docker compose up booting to green with all 4 services healthy
While the coder builds the backend (ongoing)
Run migrations against the live Postgres container and verify all 13 tables exist
Run seed data and verify with psql or a GUI tool
Pull the Ollama model -- docker exec ollama ollama pull qwen2.5 (this takes time, good to do early)
Practice inspecting containers -- docker ps, docker logs backend -f, docker exec -it postgres psql -U aijah -d aijah
Test volume persistence -- stop the stack, bring it back up, confirm Postgres data and the Ollama model are still there
Test volume reset -- docker compose down -v to wipe everything, re-run migrations, confirm clean slate
Iterate on health checks (see Part 2 below)
After basic backend routes exist
Run the full 9-step V1 demo end-to-end inside Docker
