Part 5: Phase-by-Phase Docker Architecture Changes
Phase 1 (current) -- 4 services
frontend (:3000) ─── backend (:8000) ─── postgres (:5432)
                          │
                      ollama (:11434)
                          │
                    [sandbox bind mount]
MCP server runs inside the backend process. No separate container.
Phase 2 -- 5 services (MCP extracted)
frontend (:3000) ─── backend (:8000) ─── postgres+pgvector (:5432)
                          │
                     mcp-server (:8001) ─── [sandbox bind mount]
                          │
                      ollama (:11434)
                          │
               [qwen2.5 + nomic-embed-text models]
Key Docker change: MCP server becomes its own container. Backend connects to it via http://mcp-server:8001/mcp. The MCP tool implementations and the sandbox bind mount move to this new container. Backend becomes a pure orchestrator.
Phase 3 -- 6-8 services (voice, browser control)
frontend (:3000) ─── backend (:8000) ─── postgres+pgvector (:5432)
                          │
                     mcp-server (:8001) ─── [sandbox bind mount]
                          │
                      ollama (:11434) ─── [GPU passthrough]
                          │
                    whisper-server (:8002) ─── [voice input]
                          │
                    tts-server (:8003) ─── [voice output]
This is why learning Docker networking, resource limits, and multi-service orchestration now (even if you only run 4 services) pays off massively in Phase 3.

Part 6: What to Build First (Execution Order for Docker Person)
Install Docker Desktop, verify it runs
Create docker-compose.yml with all 4 services (use the V1 contract as the spec)
Create a minimal backend/Dockerfile (just a FastAPI hello-world returning {"status": "ok"})
Create a minimal frontend/Dockerfile (nginx serving a static HTML page)
Create backend/db/migrations/001_create_enums.sql and 002_create_tables.sql from the TYPE_LEDGER and V1_CONTRACT
Mount migrations into Postgres's initdb directory
Run docker compose up and get all 4 services green
Connect to Postgres (psql or GUI) and verify all 13 tables exist
Pull qwen2.5 into Ollama: docker exec ollama ollama pull qwen2.5
Create sandbox/ directory with sample test files
Add health checks to all services
Write seed data SQL
Document the setup in a DOCKER_OPS.md playbook
After this, the Docker person is unblocked to support the coder's backend work -- running migrations for schema changes, debugging container issues, testing the full stack.
